<dl id="un1033b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un1" href="#un1033">UN1: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un1all.htm#un1033b"> (NLI.3) 33(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> rere regardant <small>color t.b.a.</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="un1033b"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/c/lexc.htm#un1033b">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/c/c86.htm#un1033b">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/c/c86.htm#un1033b">1986 (3.503)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/c/l22c.htm#un1033b">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#un1033b">MS V.A.3-18</ms> </li><li>JJA 12:256 </li><li><a name="c11d" href="../udra/u3da.htm#c11d">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/c/c11d.htm#un1033b">Draft: 3.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">As rare as the leaping lion is the lion who looks backward over his shoulder. This position is called &lsquo;regardant&rsquo; by modern armorists. The old French blazon calls it <mark><i>rere regardant</i></mark> or <i>turnaurite le visage arere</i>, &lsquo;regardant&rsquo; alone meaning simply &lsquo;looking,&rsquo; and therefore we shall describe it more reasonably in plain English as &lsquo;looking backward.&rsquo; The two-headed lion occurs in a 15th-century coat of Mason, and at the same period a monstrous lion of three bodies and one head is borne, apparently, by a Sharingbury <small> &ldquo;HERALDRY&rdquo; <a name="EBHY" href="/udra/udex.htm#EBHY"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911), p. 325/1</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Virtual page: further notes from page 32 source. </mm> </dd></dl>
